segments.text: Okay, what's your name and when were you born, sir?
My name is Martin Wiginton.
I was born here in Austin, Texas, February 4th, 1933, which makes me 52 now.
I'll give you a brief rundown on the early years of my life when I was more in the mainstream of society.
Went through high school, graduated in 1950 from Austin High, which at that point in time was the only

white high school in austin there was one black high school that austin high was one of the largest high schools in the country we graduated 1200 people the year i graduated i think during that period for nine years of my life the major thing was i was a jockstrap i played baseball and basketball and in high school at the university of texas i played baseball and then semi-pro baseball played in the army i spent
Two years in the Army in the Panama Canal Zone, 1954 to 1956 approximately, all I did there was play basketball and baseball.
I had a jock-crazy post-commandant, and he had a bunch of athletes who were privileged characters.
In fact, I had to blackmail him after nine months.
They still hadn't given me a job.
All I did was play sports, and I finally told him I wasn't going to play for him anymore if he didn't
give me some kind of job because I didn't come into the military, didn't let them draft me to play sports.
I could have done that without being in the Army.
At any rate, he gave me a job, and I spent that time in the Army.
While I was down there, I also played professional Winter League baseball, which was AA, AAA.
some major leaguers playing in it.
He made it possible for me to do that, which I think is probably illegal to be in the Army and be playing professional baseball, but we did it.
In undergraduate school in 1950-54 at the University of Texas, I studied a variety of things.
Philosophy was my major for a while, ended up to be a minor.
resources, which is a certain category of economics, and it depends on how you define disciplines, but you study resources.
I ended up getting my major in economics, which at that time is much different from the economics you have now, which is more statistical and computer stuff.
Ours was theory and how do you motivate people or how do you answer some big questions rather than how do you play with math.
Let's see, the middle 50s, 56 down in Panama, came back, knew I was going to law school.
It was the Korean War period, 54.
And what I did, I knew I wanted to go to law school, I knew that the GI Bill rights were gonna run out, and I knew I was gonna need the GI Bill to go to law school, so I requested that I be drafted
so that I would earn those educational benefits.
And I did get them.
So when I came back out of the Army, I entered UT Law School.
I had entered UT Law School before I went into the Army.
Then I dropped out of law school, went to the Army, came back, and then I had the GI Bill.
And I was courting the woman who was to become my wife.
She was a resident of Lubbock, Texas.
and going to Texas Tech.
Spent about a year courting her, going back and forth between there and here.
We got married, I guess, about 57.
Of course, that year of courting didn't do me any good in the Oscars.
I dropped out that year.
But after we got married, and Cheryl, my wife, graduated from Texas Tech.
She was a schoolteacher.
We came to Austin.
She taught school while I went to law school.
And at that point in time, I guess I actually made more money, relatively speaking, or we did, than ever since.
We lived in veterans' apartments, which cost $25 a month, all bills paid.
And I had the GI Bill, which was about $150, $200 a month, which
You'd have to multiply by four or five men to get the comparable value.
She got teachers' pay, and I worked full-time.
My brother-in-law and sister had a drive-in restaurant, and I was a manager, assistant manager there.
I didn't go to class as much.
UT Law School at that time did not require, most of the professors did not require attendance.
One of them did.
You had to be there.
And I was good at taking tests, good at studying, good at reading and cramming, and I did a lot of that.
And graduated from UT Law School in 1960.
All during this period, I was pretty, what I now think of, pretty damn naive and apolitical.
While I was in the Army, I had an experience that
that radicalized me to some extent made me madder than hell, which is generally one of the ways people become radicalized.
Eisenhower, a guy named Dwight D. Eisenhower was president.
He was coming down to Panama.
Big hoopla deal, you know, and I was on the Caribbean Command headquarters post, which is the top thing south of the United States.
He would be there, he and Mamie.
And I'll be goddamned if
the officer's club and the women's room, they didn't have, it wasn't air conditioned.
And they were afraid that Mamie might have to go in there and piss, and they spent $6,000 to air condition that women's room.
And I didn't like that the least little bit there.
I was not making hardly any money at all, and they were worried about her bathroom.
The other thing that happened when he came down there that really packed me, they had honor guards
when they brought in all these heads of state, dictators, and mostly, I guess, nine, ten-something were dictators.
Some of them might have been Democratic elected, but I don't think so, because there weren't many in South and Central America at that time.
And they'd come in, and we had honor guards, and you had to go out there and stand, and they'd play the national anthem of the country involved, and then they'd play ours.
And you had to stand at attention.
You know, you're sweating.
It was real bullshit anyway.
And the bands were playing.
And those planes would fly in.
And invariably, there would be about three planes.
The first plane would be the dictator and his official party.
And the second plane would be the mistresses and the party girls.
And the third plane would be the booze and all the gifts and payola.
And then we had to cart that shit.
Well, the way I was raised, it went against my grain for me as a human being, an individual, to have to carry the luggage of some fucking dictator.
I mean, I don't dig that shit.
You can carry your own, but I didn't do anything.
I carried the luggage and went on about it.
But I know it made a big impression on me, and I didn't like it.
Well, back to the latter part of the 50s, I had several good friends in law school that got to know real well.
They're very good lawyers now around the state with big law firms who were very close.
But it was during that time that I began to, I think it was, it's hard to pin things down, but I think it was during that time that I began to
get more liberal or progressive in my views.
I knew that all the shit that was coming down about racism and black people was a cut and dried issue.
I mean, and yet you were hearing a lot of bullshit about you gotta keep up traditions and they're better off this way than any other way and blah blah.
And at any rate, I graduated from law school in 1960s.
My friends went other ways, some of them practicing law in Houston, some in Amarillo, and some in Dallas.
My wife and I had quite purposely not had any children while we were in law school.
But after we settled down to practice law in El Campo, a little town down on the Gulf Coast between Houston and Victoria, she taught school there and I practiced law.
El Campo's in Horton County.
It's an area that's very rich in resources and agriculture and minerals.
Outside of the urban counties in Texas, it's one of, I think it is, the richest.
It's got about
14 to 16 different national origins of people that live in Horton County.
Every year their county fair type thing is an all nations festival where the people dress up.
They still do this.
They dress up in their costumes and have the food and the music and all of that.
But I had kinfolks there.
That's where my daddy's family had homesteaded back in the 1890s.
And
My kinfolks were rice farmers and cattle ranchers.
They'd been poor as hell during the Depression, the 1930 period.
I think one of them had everything sold out from Hungary.
But the World War II, they got quite wealthy.
They were good farmers.
It was much easier to get credit and get the equipment to do the rice farming and the cattle ranching.
And those two

efforts go together, I don't know if you're familiar with it or not, but generally speaking they grow rice on land one year and then they let it lay out for a year or two and that year or two it's laying out is when they graze cattle on it and it helps the cattle and the cattle fertilize the land and it helps rebuild the land.
It's a pretty good system.
At any rate, they were there and they helped me set up a lawn practice and we
My wife became pregnant, and we had our first daughter within a year from the time we moved there.
At this point, let me say that I have three daughters.
Cheryl, her name is Cheryl Lemon.
She was from Lubbock.
Cheryl and I lived together for seven and a half years.
She had all three girls by cesarean section, which means they have to cut the woman open to get the baby out because of delivery problems.
We were together during the three years of law school, then several years in El Campo, and then a couple of years after we moved back to Austin.
And then we broke up and divorced, and she moved back to Lubbock and remarried.
Had twin boys then by cesarean section.
At any rate, I have three daughters.
They're great girls, great women now.
All of them, two of them are graduates of Texas Tech and one of them's about halfway through studying art.
The middle girl is in the Air Force now as an intelligence officer out in Denver reading, I think what she does is read satellite photographs and interpret them for fighter pilots, but I'm not sure.
My ex-wife and I get along quite well.

In addition to being naive about politics and social activism during the 1950s, during the 50s and 60s, it was all a big learning experience for me about sex and sexual relations and the way people ought to treat each other.
And certainly I didn't treat my wife the way I should have.
She was a very fine person.
We had a lot of good times.

I was very deceitful with her, and it took me a period of six or eight years probably to work out a lot of the problems that I think most men and women have, or at least of that generation and that time had of being able to communicate and handle each other's desires and needs.
You just want to keep going chronologically through, kind of through my life, or do you want to get back to questions?
That was good.
I mean, I don't care.
I'm getting ready to get into the radical part.
Describe the hippie scene in Austin in the 60s.
Let me first say that I have some problems with the term hippie.
Okay, define the word hippie then.
I mean, whatever.
It is.

It was used in a lot of derogatory ways by the media and by politicians and by public opinion, so-called public opinion makers, to put down a variety of things, some of which I thought were, at that time, pretty apolitical.
I now have a broader view of what's political than I did then, but that whole
so-called hippie scene, I think, had a profound impact on society.
It changed me.
I mean, I never was a hippie.
I never considered myself a hippie.
Because it made, they were more honest.
Their idea was and is that people should be honest with each other.
People should love one another.
People should try to help one another.
And most times in our society, people do not do those things.
They are not honest, and they don't make conscious efforts to try to help one another or love one another.
And I guess one of the general definitions would be that the hippies used a lot of dope.
And if you're going to fool with that kind of term, I guess you could say that
Yeah, hippies did introduce to this society the idea that different drugs have a lot to offer people.
And in my experience, that proved correct.
I say my experience, I don't mean me personally, because the only drugs that I've experienced are marijuana two or three times.
But it has an effect on me that I don't particularly like.
It makes me where I can't talk.
And I'm a verbal person, and if I'm having a lot of thoughts and a lot of good things to feel and say and not be able to say them, then I don't like it.
Also, back during the early 50s, as was fairly common then, I used speed one time when I'd been up for 48 hours or two or three days studying.
And hashish, I experienced that one time during the 60s, but only once.
And all that is concentrated marijuana.
I mean, it's very heavy.
It really cools you out.
What I remember about the marijuana and hashish experience is it makes you much more sensitive to color and sound.
and your own bodily feelings.
But I didn't like the other effects enough where I didn't do it.
Now, what I did do for 30 years, I drank hard.
I boozed hard from the time I was in my senior prom in 1950.
for 30 years.
Lots of beer, lots of alcohol, vodka, gin, you name it.
I've drunk it in great quantities.
I quit about three and a half or four years ago and it got to be too much of a burden and too long of hangovers.
So that was my drug, was alcohol.
But to get back to the hippies, I think they had a profound, I know they had a profound influence on our whole society.
They made working people, so-called redneck bikers,

jocks all re-examined who they were and how they were treating people themselves and other people hippies were really open they were willing to run tremendous risks as far as physical abuse or verbal abuse but I mean they ran dangerous risks just by the way they looked and acted which was much much different from the norm then
And all of this, at that early stage, I would not have considered too political.
But now I do, because it does affect how people relate.
And I know that it had an effect.
It had a big effect on the army, the men in the army.
And they were very loving, open people, were willing to be warm and close with them.
even knowing that they had major differences about what each was doing with their own lives.
Army men were getting ready to go to Vietnam and kill people, and the hippies were saying, no, don't do that, that isn't a good thing to do.
And yet, there was enough openness and sincerity where it worked out.
The hippie scene...

We had a lot of, the hippie scene was, to a large extent, I thought, centered originally out in California, and we had a lot of interchange between San Francisco and Austin, people that lived here and traveled out there and came back.
And then later on, during the 60s, a lot of people traveling between Austin and New York City, Madison, Wisconsin, Michigan, the more hotbed
centers of student activism.
But see, to me, that gets away from hippies.

Hippies, in a way, they would show up for a major demonstration or a major political action, but they were not the ones who day in and day out worked on trying to get together educational materials, did research, call meetings,
did the planning for demonstration.
All of the things that go into political activism, most hippies were not heavily involved in.
But they would participate whenever something made sense to them, and participate in good ways.
So they were a big political force, but I always wished they had been more
more concerted and more intensive in what they were doing.
But so be it.
Does that hand come close to talking about what you needed on that?
Okay.
Was there a difference between anti-war people and hippies?
That's something that I just said.
I like it.
I'd say 98% of the hippies were anti-war people.

There might have been 2% that were so spaced out that they wouldn't vocalize or state a position on it, but war and that whole notion is directly contrary to what I understand to be a hippie set of principles.
The anti-war people are the ones that I think of as more organized, more concerted and intensive in their efforts
the anti-war movement was made up of a number of different elements.
I'll kind of give you a rundown on what my analysis is and how it was made up, how it was grouped.
Of course, when you're talking about the left in the United States, you're not talking about a highly organized
discipline structured thing.
It didn't happen that way.
There were some groups that were highly organized and disciplined that then worked together in the larger meetings to try to influence the politics of it.
There were a lot of sectarian groups, what I call sectarian people, who had a rigid set of beliefs.
A lot of them were Marxist-Leninists.
who some of the groups, progressive labor, the Trotskyists, if you want to be nasty, you call them Trotskyites, but Trotskyists is a fraternal way to talk about it on the left.
The Communist Party, the CP, which is about as liberal as the Democratic Party.
I mean, it's really the Communist Party of the United States is a very milquetoast, lukewarm group.
as far as, I mean they believe in electoral politics and lots of dialogue and debate and they're very careful about being law abiding.
But you had the sectarian groups, another significant element in the anti-war movement was there were the church groups, the Quakers, the pacifists.
Then you had
the hippies and the students that, as I indicated a minute ago, would show up, would participate in major events or certain things.
The main thrust of the anti-war movement, where all the heavy duty stuff came from, where the student activists, the new left people, the SDS,
The national groups in the anti-war movement were called the mobilization mob, it was called.
And whenever a particular event would come up, there'd almost always be a different grouping of national organizations that would come together and form an ad hoc, one-time structure to handle it.
But where the guts of those things came from, the big ones, the highly successful ones,
were the New Left SDS people.
Those were the ones that I really identified with.
And I guess, I think now, the only organization that I remember or that I'm proud of being a part of was SDS.
Even though I was a different age level, they had a broad definition of what a student was.
As do I, I'm a student of life and we're all students and teachers and anybody that gets into narrow categories on those subjects is making a mistake.
At any rate, SDS and the New Left people gave the big thrust to it.
There were some

some few dave delger in particular comes to mind is is one who for years had been active in a very organized disciplined way although he wasn't in any sectarian group i think he's probably a a non-violent i know he's a non-violent pacifist approach now that does not mean that i mean passive towards
human life.
I mean, he doesn't believe in taking human life.
That does not mean he wouldn't destroy our property or something of that sort.
There's all kinds of distinctions that come up.
But Dellinger was one of the few big national leaders who had several decades of experience before the 60s.
I think he spent the early part of most of World War II in jail because he wasn't willing to go military.
because of his social convictions, political convictions.
Okay, the anti-war movement, it shifted forms from time to time depending on what the event was, whether it was national, regional, local.
There were major fights to control the politics of those events.
I don't think the Communist Party ever
wielded much influence.
The Trotskyists caused quite a bit of conflict I think up east where they have a number of old left traditions going back 50, 60, 70 years.
People who came over from Europe who were socialists or revolutionaries and a lot of them were Trotskyists or became Trotskyists after the mess in Russia occurred when Stalin brutalized and murdered
A lot of people in the 1930s, a lot of people left the so-called Communist Party and became Trotskyists or various things.
But I know we had some problems here in Austin with the Trotskyist groups, but they never were in tune enough with the major number of people around to have a whole lot of influence.
They were always very law-abiding.
They always wanted to have highly...
disciplined approach to a demonstration.
I mean, they didn't want any spontaneity or anybody doing something that hadn't been discussed and agreed upon by then, which didn't work in Austin.
They'd say, fuck you, we're going to go.
You do what you want to do, and we'll do what we're going to do, and we'll meet you down there if you want to come.
But they're very...
If you know your politics very well, you know that the old left sectarians are very much like the so-called moral majority people.
They're very puritanical and believe their way is right and you've got to live a rigid... No dope, no smoking, no fucking...
They've got screwed up notions about everything that's fun in life.
If you like alcohol and sex and music and dancing and things like that, then the old left and the moral majority have a lot in common.
They're all backed up.
Now, that's kind of a general overview about the anti-war movement.
Are there more specifics?
That was good.
I mean, we got an overview there of Austin at the time.
Okay, now I'll very broad define the movement.
I've been trying to think all week, trying to remember a lot of this to make it easier to talk about.
In the first place, the movement was made up of a number of different groups, individuals, and ideas.
So I can only tell you what I think of as a movement and what I think was kind of a general thing as far as highly political people, which I consider myself to be, how they viewed it.
In the early 60s, the movement was the Civil Rights Movement, primarily concerned with racism and civil rights, and I participated in that heavily.
A little later,
It became involved in the Southeast Asian war situation.
Another aspect of it was student rights, student rebellion against authority structures and a lot of the ways that universities and their life was structured.
There's a very good paper called Student as Nigger.

I don't know whether you've ever read it or not, but it lays out what at that time was thought of as a pretty good view about how certain people are channeled and they try to make people fit into molds.
Another part of the movement in Texas, not true in all states, but certainly true in Texas, was the farm workers, La Raza.

During the early and middle 60s there were a number of fairly major demonstrations which finally years and years later enough pressure was exerted where they attained some legislation that was beneficial.
But part of the movement was Chicano rights or Chicano issue oriented.

In the latter 60s and early 70s, there was a growth or more focus and conscious effort as far as the relationship between sexes, women, the women's movement, which was part of what I think of as the movement.
By my view, you could not be a member of

you weren't an authentic member of the movement unless you had certain good views about all of these issues in other words but we were all realists too i mean we knew that some people or anymore who were very macho and racist so you tried to have an impact on all of that at the same time you're working on whatever the event was at the time
And there were some major arguments and major fights.

And that was one of the beautiful things about all of those days was those meetings and the interchange between people about how they looked at life, how they treated each other, whether they were racist, whether they were sexist, whether they were fair to each other.
And it caused a lot of changes.
I think the women's movement at least has had some margin of success at changing some of the Chicano macho culture.
I mean, I think it's had an impact on it.
I'm not saying it radically changed, but it's obvious it hadn't.
Well, it's substantially changed from what it was 20 years ago, believe me.
In the early, there was a progression that went on.
In the early 60s, all these various issues were addressed by various groups and individuals.
Major efforts were made.
You guys doing okay?
I'd like some coffee.
Okay.
And results were not obtained, and there was a radicalization process that went on.
I mean, you keep appealing to reason.
I mean, you keep saying, Mr.
Congressman, Mr.
Senator, Mr. President, Mr.
Governor, you know, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.
For ABC reasons, you ought to do this, and all they do is give you bullshit and weasel around and continue to do what is obviously the thing they shouldn't do,
you finally understand that there's shit in this house.
Something stinks.
It ain't working.
Don't tell me that it does.
Let me say at this point that I work professionally in liberal Democratic Party politics.
In the early 1960s, I was part of a statewide organization called the Texas Democratic Coalition.
I was a statewide field director of that group, and we had 23 projects around the state in all the major cities which had significant minority representation, blacks and Chicanos.

And we had an organization that got, at that point in time, it was considered major amounts of money from an outfit called the Voter Education Project out of Atlanta, Georgia, which in turn got its money originally from
The up east old liberal families like the Stern Foundation, the Kennedys, Marshall.
There are two or three of the old big rich families up east that are liberal oriented.

They pipelined money down to the voter education project, which then put it out to various places, like the Texas Democratic Coalition, which then did a lot of voter registration and get out the vote work.
And I was involved full-time, paid professional with that effort.
And at that point, we had the most volunteer workers.
I don't know whether they've passed it now.
I guess they have.
But I know doing that in one year, we had something like 14,000 volunteers and block workers in major cities.
And we increased the black voter registration in the Chicanos dramatically during that period.
I also worked for a guy for a year and a half who ran for governor, a man named Don Yarborough, who almost beat John Connolly in 1960.
Yeah, 1960.
I think Connolly won that thing by less than a percentage point.
Then I worked for the Democratic Coalition.
I eventually became the state executive secretary of that, which was the top position.
Larry Goodwin, the guy I was talking about a minute ago, at that point, he's the one who got me into that Democratic Coalition to start with.
He had a profound impact on my life.
He was a speechwriter and a very intelligent person.
And he was the first executive secretary of the Democratic Coalition.
He worked in the campaigns of Ralph Yarber, the senator at that time, Don Yarber.
I did all those things and worked with Larry, too.

learned a lot from him in later years and he went back to the University of Texas, got his PhD in history and now is a tenured professor of history over at Duke and writes books published by the Oxford University Press about populism and radicalism in the South and he's the one who's the oral history, has a big interest in oral history.
Okay, so I went through that, I'm a pro, or I was,
20 years ago at Democratic Party politics, we had a lot of major convention fights.
John Kennedy, Jack Kennedy, of course, they got money to us.
They did not like Lyndon Johnson and his brand of politics, but they were in bed with him.
It had to be if they figured to win.
But at the same time, they were feeding us money, hoping that that situation would change.
the year that, of course, Lyndon Johnson hated our guts and we hated his.
But when Jack Kennedy got killed and Lyndon became president, then that became too much for the organized Texas liberal Democrats at that point in time.
Lyndon as president just exerted too much power.
As vice president,
with his connections with major oil and major industries and finance people.
He had lots of power, but nothing like what you have whenever you're the top electoral official.
And he cut off that money from the East.
It came down to the Voter Education Project.
Of course, a lot of the money came from the Voter Education Project.
A lot of it came from the AFL-CIO unions.
And, of course, I'll never forget the way he fucked over the United Auto Workers and the steel workers and made them cave in on a lot of the Democratic Party convention fights.
He didn't have to come down here to Texas.
Neither did Walter Ruther, who was in the head of the UAW.
I mean, they'd sit up there and cut their deals, make a deal.
I think the guy's name was McDonald, who was head of the steel workers then.
He was an asshole.
They'd cut a deal with Linden, and then they'd pick up the phone and call their top guy in Texas, and those were two of the biggest unions in Texas, tremendous power inside the Lakeland.
And they'd say, bullshit, don't do that liberal thing.
You do what Linden wants you to do.
We're going to have something just happen on our contract.
There's going to be so many millions spent on that aircraft plant.
But don't fuck around.
I'm a pro.
I mean, I know how that shit works, which makes me fully realize that democracy does not exist.

It is something that I want to see exist, and it's, I think, an attainable goal, but people in the United States should not fool themselves into thinking that they have a democracy, because they do not.
It's highly rigged.
It depends upon the media and who's got the money and
who controls the educational system.
And a lot of, I mean, you have to take a pretty examined study of it to understand how people are channeled and manipulated.
There's not any tight conspiracy by capitalists.
I don't believe that shit.
But it is obvious that they've got a community of interest and they damn sure do their homework.
And ABC, NBC, CBS are all controlled by the same kind of people.
They're all people who
have the vested interest, the status quo at heart.
And they don't want to see changes.
Same way with all the major corporations owned by, or controlled, owned and controlled by the same kind of folks.
And they take care of their homework as far as the legislatures and the congresses and the school boards and the city councils.
There's occasional slip-ups, but they have enough safeguards where nothing ever runs wild.
You might get a city who
think they're going to do some zoning out somewhere outside their city limits to protect their aquifer.
But then they'll soon find out from their lawyers and all that that belongs to the county government.
And then you'll find out that the state never has given the county governments the right to zone.
So that means that the developers get to do whatever the fuck they want to out there.
So it's a pretty sophisticated system that exists, but it looks after the major interests of property owners and profit-motivated
So democracy doesn't exist.
You can go through the academic bullshit, which a lot of teachers and professors like to do, but I don't think it's worthwhile where you can say, well, it's better here than it's better there.
To me, we've got lousy situations in most of the world.
And the question is, what can we do about it?
And the major thing is we gotta speak the truth.
I mean, you can't lie, you can't bullshit each other.
So that's why I always try to make the point that we do not have a democratic system.
It is highly controlled.
You do not get on the media to express opinions that are contrary to the major thing.
By the way, on this very subject, I did run for governor in 1968.

Yeah, that's when Lyndon, I was working with the, you know, I've been doing a lot of different things all during that period of time, and I was working with a lot of the SDS New Left people out at the University of Texas, and Lyndon was president, Vietnam War, the Civil Rights Movement, all of those things were getting a lot of attention.
That election was coming up, and
And I'm adding it's still true today.
The way the law read then, the television networks do not have to save you time if you want to go on television with spots about the war and racism and poverty.
They do not have to let you own that tube.
Don't ever be naive enough to think that if you get the money together that you can buy spots.
You can if they want you to.

But the exception to that, according to their theory and their law, is that if you're a candidate, an officially declared candidate, then they have to sell you the time on the same basis they do the others.
So all of us knew that.
We wanted to mount a television campaign on those three issues, war and racism and poverty.
